The SSID of standalone WIFII AP is incorrectly formatted as Roaster000000 instead of Roaster followed by last six digits of the MAC address, The reason WiFi.macAddress() is still returning zeros is due to a known quirk in the ESP32/ESP8266 network stack initialization timing: even after calling WiFi.mode(), the high-level wrapper can sometimes fail to query the system registers fast enough before the radio interface fully boots up. To solve this permanently, we can bypass the high-level WiFi.macAddress() wrapper entirely and call the native ESP-IDF hardware function esp_read_mac(). This function pulls the unique factory-burned MAC address directly from the chip's eFuse registers. It works instantly at boot time regardless of the current Wi-Fi state or mode.Additionally, the string assignment inside computeDynamicAPProperties needs to explicitly set the base name to "Roaster" instead of appending to the global string instance, which avoids compound appending bugs.





